Subject:    <a href="?t=95837891400044&r=1&w=2">name choice, followup to my recent question</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837816800022&r=1&w=2">"Craig A. Finseth" &lt;fin () unet ! unet ! umn ! edu&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=199002">1990-02-27 17:20:29</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326873&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837797326873&q=raw">body</a>]</b>


My question was whether "net.umn.edu" was a reasonable sub-domain
name.  The answer is no.  Several people pointed out a real problem:
name translation into and out of the U.K.  In particular, mailers
would tend to try to look up the name "edu.umn.net" and not succeed.

This problem can occur with *any* initial name component that matches
*any* top-level domain (e.g., you don't want to call a host
"fr.abc.umn.edu" let it be mistakenly converted to "edu.umn.abc.fr").

As it turned out, there was no consensus for a name to change to.
Thus, we selected "unet.umn.edu" (for University NETworking) and have
made all of the appropriate changes.

Thank you for your help,.

